\begin_layout Standard
The easy pair separates earlier and more cleanly than the hard pair.
 This is compatible with the hypothesis that the transformer uses context to perform Bayesian-like inference over the identity of the generating process.
 However,
 there is no separating into linear,
 disjoint subspaces for any context as might have been expected;
 rather,
 the same dimensions appear to be reused.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Flow fields conditioned on incoming evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous sections have focussed on analyzing the residual stream jointly over all sequence positions,
 in a way visualizing the marginal 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s_{t})=\sum_{x_{t}}P(s_{t}|x_{t})P(x_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 In this section,
 I now want to ask about dynamics:
 can we indeed treat each incoming token as a directional update to the residual stream,
 depending on the token?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To this end,
 for each position 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 I visualized the velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\bm{h}=\bm{h}_{t+1}-\bm{h}_{t}$
\end_inset

 in PCA space,
 conditioned on the incoming token 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t+1}\in\{0,1,2\}$
\end_inset

 (Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:flow"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Each column corresponds to one token value:
 each row to one layer.
 We chose this analysis because the theoretical framework in Q2 predicts that incoming evidence 
\begin_inset Formula $\log P(x_{t}|\bm{s}_{t})$
\end_inset

 should act as a velocity in latent space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each token drives the representation in a characteristic direction,
 suggesting the transformer implements approximate belief updates where each token pushes the latent representation toward the simplex vertex associated with that token's preferred hidden state.
\end_layout

